"We were there."

When you are here, there is no other thing that matters, nothing distracts you, the sounds fill your mind, scent from the flames replaces your breath and you lose yourself. Lose yourself on the ghats, on a warm summer evening in Varanasi.

The feeling is subconscious, if you are really present here. It catches you off-guard. Then the summer heat of 45 degrees, squeezing and force fitting in the mass cannot even matter. 

Stills from this year's to last year's visit.

latestPosts.caption:
"The Prayer."

The prayer sequence for the Ganga Aarti is a performance by the Poojaris (Pandits) that is a spectacle of rhythm, self coordination and sync. 

The pictures here, can only depict the beauty and the colors of the ceremony and to some extent, the mood. The experience? I hope you are there when you visit Varanasi.

latestPosts.caption:
"The Assi Ghat."

I recall telling my Bhutanese classmates, "If you want to find tranquility, visit Varanasi." without even having the slightest idea about the city's culture. 

But as you walk through the ancient city, mapping your way through the narrow gullies, hearing the daily motion around you, the city starts to open herself up with a warmth that makes you want to believe that you are now part of something bigger - something from the past, a reality that is long gone by.

I am not a religious guy but to have gotten a chance to visit it twice, within a year? I'd like to believe there's a blessing at play here. Maybe it's there somewhere in the video.
